## 2. The Problem

### Problem Statement

Millions of Indian girls and women are living with PMOS without a diagnosis, without culturally relevant support, and without anyone who truly understands what they are experiencing — clinically or emotionally.

### Specific Problems Being Solved

**Problem 1 — Detection happens too late**  
Most women are diagnosed with PMOS years after symptoms begin. The average diagnostic delay in India is approximately 2 years. During this time, the condition progresses untreated and the emotional impact compounds.

**Problem 2 — Schools have no screening mechanism**  
Teenage girls aged 13–18 are the highest-risk window for PMOS onset. There is currently no structured, accessible screening programme in Indian schools. Girls leave school without ever knowing their symptoms have a name.

**Problem 3 — Existing apps are not built for Indian women**  
Every major period tracking or PMOS management app uses Western food references, Western cultural context, and prediction algorithms that fail for irregular cycles — which is the defining symptom of PMOS.

**Problem 4 — The emotional reality of PMOS is completely ignored**  
Research confirms that women with PMOS have a 2.5x higher probability of depression, significantly higher rates of anxiety, reduced self-esteem, and identity disruption. No existing app addresses this. No companion feature. No emotional support. No acknowledgement that this condition affects who you feel you are — not just your body.

**Problem 5 — Girls have no one to talk to who truly understands**  
Family dismisses symptoms as normal. Friends don't understand the emotional intensity. Doctors give 10-minute appointments. Women with PMOS are consistently left alone with an experience that is difficult to explain and even harder to manage without support.

